article.description:
Tamecka Dixon scored 20 points and the Los
Angeles Sparks defeated the Utah Starzz 102-75 Sunday night for their second blowout victory in three days.
article.headline: Leslie gets healthy with birthday bashing of Starzz
article.linkText: Sparks tie club scoring record in rout of Starzz
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lisa Leslie showed she's almost back to her
old self.

	   Bothered for 2½ weeks by a flulike ailment that caused her to
lose 10 pounds, Leslie had 13 points and eight rebounds as the Los
Angeles Sparks defeated the Utah Starzz 102-75 Sunday night for
their second blowout victory in three days.

	   "I'm feeling much better,'' said Leslie, who has regained 5
pounds and is keeping herself hydrated after complaining of feeling
tired and weak at times.

	   Leslie turned 30 Sunday, and among her gifts was a dozen red
roses, purses, jewelry, candles and a Los Angeles Lakers blanket
from teammate DeLisha Milton. Fans held up homemade signs wishing
her happy birthday.

	   "The biggest present of all is a win because I did not want to
lose,'' she said.

	   There was no danger of that.

	   Tamecka Dixon had 20 points and eight of the Sparks' 27 assists.

	   Mwadi Mabika and Milton added 17 points each as all 11 Sparks
played. They tied the franchise record for most points, which also
came against Utah in a 102-70 victory on June 28, 1999.

	   "Our offensive execution was great, and it's nice to score 100
points,'' said Sparks coach Michael Cooper, who did that often as a
member of the Lakers' championship teams of the 1980s.

	   Leslie, who on Sunday was announced as the Western Conference's
starting center for the July 15 WNBA All-Star game, picked up her
fifth foul and left the game with 11:40 remaining.

	   "She's getting a little more energy with every game,'' Dixon
said.

	   The Sparks were coming off an 87-56 victory against Sacramento
on Friday at Staples Center, and they had it just as easy against
the Starzz.

	   "In the first part of our season, we didn't do a good job of
closing teams out,'' Dixon said. "We'd had big leads on people.
We're definitely trying to get that killer instinct back.''

	   Adrienne Goodson led Utah with 14 points and nine rebounds.
Natalie Williams was held to six points and had six turnovers.

	   The Starzz scored the game's first basket, then never led again.

	   "It was just an old-fashioned butt-kicking,'' Utah coach Candi
Harvey said. "They were red-hot, on top of their game offensively,
and when they play like that, they're pretty tough to beat.''

	   Leslie connected on her first three shots, launching the Sparks
to a 27-11 lead that was built while shooting nearly 77 percent.
They were 7-for-10 from 3-point range in the first half.

	   "They certainly came out on fire,'' Starzz guard Jennifer Azzi
said. "It's to their credit for shooting so well, but at the same
time, we didn't play well defensively. You can't start like that
against them.''

	   Utah cut its 20-point deficit to nine just before rookie Nikki
Teasley hit a 3-pointer to give the Sparks a 52-40 halftime lead.

	   "The three at the end of the half really knocked us down,''
Harvey said. "We had gotten to only nine, and then the three put
us way back and killed our momentum.''

	   Dixon did most of her damage at the start of the second half,
scoring 10 of the Sparks' first 17 points as they took a 69-48
lead.

	   "We did a great job of concentrating on defending them and just
pushing it at them offensively,'' she said. "I'm really happy with
the way we played.''

	   Utah never made a run in the second half and trailed by 30
points with four minutes remaining. The Starzz shot 36 percent for
the game and were outrebounded 42-27.
